		<hr />
		
		
			<div><strong>Increasing Difficulty and Healer Balance</strong><br />&nbsp;</div>
		
		
		
		<div>A month into GoD, EverQuest has come to a crossroads.<br />
<br />
As the game progresses further along, more difficult encounters must be designed in order to keep players feeling challenged as they accumulate better gear.  In GoD, as with other expansions, this has been achieved through increasing the damage output of mobs.  In order to compensate, a group must increase its ability to heal.  With one class drastically superior in healing power, this leaves us with a serious problem; both now, and as EverQuest continues to grow.<br />
<br />
Before you say it, yes, I know- clerics have always been the superior healers.  My question is- why?  For a long time, there has been equity in tanking (although once again, as single group encounters in GoD start to require defensive, this is no longer as true as it once was); for almost every single group encounter pre-GoD, there was no reason to choose a warrior over a paladin, or a shadow knight over a warrior.  There is equity in slowing; while shamans have a slightly superior slow, there is no major difference between having a beastlord slower, an enchanter slower, or a shaman slower.  There is equity in DPS; a few classes sit at the top, trading places based on circumstances, and there are a few other classes below who have secondary abilities to compensate.  In GoD, most specifically anything from Sewers 1 on up, you are <i>required</i> to have a cleric healer, in addition to a secondary healer.  As you progress upwards, this changes from one cleric healer and one other healer to two cleric healers.<br />
<br />
What I am about to say violates nearly every urge in my mind which rails against the idea, but I truly think it is best for the future of EverQuest.<br />
<br />
Druids need to become nearly as good at healing as clerics are currently.<br />
<br />
For the sake of the future of EverQuest, the cleric dominance over the healing spot in groups needs to be broken.  They should be the best healers; but the gap is much too large now.  A warriors advantage over a paladin or shadow knight is 5% extra damage mitigation and a few hundred hit points.  The difference between the two top slowing classes is 75% vs. 70%.  Let's now compare the difference between clerics and druids, as the two top healing classes.<br />
<br />
<u>Large Scale Healing</u><br />
Clerics: <a href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=13&amp;source=Live" target="_blank">Complete Healing</a>, 7500hp, 400 mana, 10 sec cast time<br />
Druids: <a href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=3232&amp;source=Live" target="_blank">Karana's Renewal</a>, 4680hp, 600 mana, 10 sec cast time, limited to 75% of a targets total health.<br />
<br />
<u>Blast Healing</u><br />
Clerics: <a href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=4880&amp;source=Live" target="_blank">Holy Light</a>, 3750hp, 650 mana, 3.75 cast time<br />
Druids:  <a href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=4883&amp;source=Live" target="_blank">Sylvan Infusion</a>, 2100hp, 550 mana, 3.75 cast time<br />
<br />
In addition to these basic building blocks of healing, clerics also get regen heals (best of which is <a href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=4882&amp;source=Live" target="_blank">Holy Light</a>), group heals (<a href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=3471&amp;source=Live" target="_blank">Word of Replenishment</a>), and a plethora of AA heals, including Divine Arbitration and Celestial Renewal.  I should not have to struggle to make my case that cleric healing is drastically more powerful than druid healing.<br />
<br />
The question is, if we increase druids healing power, how do we compensate for the other abilities druids have in regards to cleric balance?<br />
<br />
Well, the abilities they have aren't drastically different in terms of balance.  They both have damage shields, although a clerics is less efficient.  They both have root; druids additionally get snare.  Druids DPS is superior to cleric DPS, although with hammers, this isn't as much as a difference as it once was.  Druids also have resist buffs and debuffs.  I would make the case here that no secondary abilities need to be altered in order to maintain relative balance.<br />
<br />
Druids should be given better heals, or have their current series improved.  A good target would be for druid healing to be 85-90% of what a clerics is.  Clerics should maintain superior HP buffs, in addition to a wider diversity of healing.  Druids should never get group heals or short duration regen heals; however, <b>they should be able to substitute for a cleric as the primary healer for a group</b>.  As EverQuest becomes more challenging and requires more healing power, it cannot continue to have clerics be the overwhelmingly predominant healing force.</div>
	</td>
</tr>
