		<div>Why have Clerics always been the superior healers by a bit?  Probably because it's the only thing we do.  Yeah, sure, we have nukes and &quot;cool&quot; hammers... but ever try to nuke with a Cleric?  I rarely have one mem'd because it's just pointless.  Soloing with hammers?  Good for a laugh, but that's about it.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				good target would be for druid healing to be 85-90% of what a clerics is.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
No, sorry.  Druids should be <b>at the very most</b> around 65-70% of what a Cleric is.  They're already hovering around 45-50% as is (they're also about 45-50% of a Wizard in terms of nuking... sometimes higher).  You need to remember that Druids don't just heal.  They can nuke well, they can dot well, they can solo very well... three things a Cleric cannot do well at all.  In standard group situations a Druid should be able to substitute for a Cleric.  In most cases they can.  In raid / difficult group situations (ie. Ikkinz trials) they should be secondary healers only.  Druids need some slight buffs in regards to healing, but nothing major.<br />
<br />
You bring up CH.  Well, while the Druid CH could stand to be upped, it's rather pointless these days.  Ask most Druids how often they cast CH since GoD... hell, ask most Clerics.  I rarely use it, I'm mostly using Holy Light / Holy Elixir for heals instead.  CH is just too slow.<br />
<br />
Shaman on the other hand, they need some work in the healing department.</div>
	</td>
</tr>
</table>
