		<hr />
		
		
		
		
		<div>Plain and simple, Shamans and druids need a heal upgrade.<br />
Find something unique to do with their heals though.<br />
Clerics have the big number, straight out heals. They should have them at the lowest mana cost and/or the fastest casting time.<br />
<br />
Give shamans a reverse canni heal.<br />
Sucks away from their mana bar as though it were a dot, and have it add to tank health for as long as that lasts. And allow other spells to be cast while that one is in effect. WIthout looking at the numbers, Let's say 700 health per tick for 350 mana per tick. Give it a 10 tick duration with a near-zero casting cost, and bam. Suddenly the heals a shaman has, which can be used on top of that, are more useful. Even VoQ wouldn't help the shaman much here. You'd have to time it right, and if you needed to, you could canni.<br />
<br />
You'd have a shaman who's feeding his/her magickal power into the spirit world, to provide healing for someone else.<br />
They'd have to code it so it couldn't be used on self, but *shrug*<br />
<br />
Give druids a self-stunning heal. If the druid was the main healer, this would limit the amount of DoT casting they'd be able to do, at least a bit. Give them a full CH just like that of a cleric, with the addition of a 5 or 10 second stun afterwards, rather like our harvest spell. Now they have a choice, heal like a cleric, losing most of your other class benefits, or perform your normal old duties.<br />
Voile! Something that almost slightly resembles balance, just a little.<br />
<br />
Clerics would still be preferred. Shamans have to worry about mana in a major way under this system. If they don't keep an eye on it. *stomp* it's a wipe.<br />
This gives you the ability to take another class as an effective healer, without removing clerics from the lineup. The other healing classes will now have the choice to either heal effectively, or operate within their normal roles.<br />
<br />
Lemme know what you think, I'm just running off at the mouth here.</div>
	</td>
</tr>
